            <fr:addr type="user">plt-languages-0006</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>plt-languages-0006.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Small-step operational semantics of the addition language">Small-step operational semantics of the addition language</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The <fr:link type="local" href="plt-semantics-0005.xml" addr="plt-semantics-0005" title="Small-step operation semantics">small-step operational semantics</fr:link> of the <fr:link type="local" href="plt-languages-0001.xml" addr="plt-languages-0001" title="An addition language">addition
language</fr:link> is given below.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The first rule is the <fr:em>reduction rule</fr:em> (or <fr:em>contraction rule</fr:em>). It specified how
the basic operation (here, addition) can be performed. Expressions matching this rule are
called <fr:em>reducible expressions</fr:em> or <fr:em>redexes</fr:em>:

<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\frac {}{\text {Add}\ (\text {Val}\ n)\ (\text {Val}\ m) \rightarrow  \text {Val}\ (n + m)}]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>The last two rules are <fr:em>structural rules</fr:em> (or <fr:em>congruence rules</fr:em>) that define how
larger terms can be reduced:

<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\frac {x\rightarrow  x'}{\text {Add}\ x\ y \rightarrow  \text {Add}\ x'\ y}]]></fr:tex>
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\frac {y\rightarrow  y'}{\text {Add}\ x\ y \rightarrow  \text {Add}\ x\ y'}]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
